text:
Madison Avenue, at the N. E. corner of East 25th Street, showing the white mabble structure housing the Appellate Division of the Supreme Court. Extending its greater length on 25th Street, it is entered from there.

About 1900

H. N. Tiemann, photo
Gift of Urbrock Collection

Madison Avenue, at the N. E. corner of East 25th Street, showing the entrance to the Appellate Division of the Supreme Court building.

Madison Ave., east side, from but not including 25th to and including 26th Streets, a part of Madison Square Garden shown in the left background. The view also shows 26th Street, north side, west from 19 East 26th Street, east to and including Madison Ave. The N.E. corner of Madison Square Park is shown in the foreground.

About 1923.

Ewing Galloway.

Madison Square, the N.E. corner of the park, showing Madison Avenue between 25th and 26th Streets, and Madison Square Garden, the year before its demolition.

Summer 1924.

P.L. Sperr, Photographer.

East 25th Street, north side, east from Madison to Fourth Aves., as viewed across an empty lot at the S.E. corner of Madison Ave. upon which stood the Madison Ave. Building and others. Prominently shown is the Appellate Division of the Supreme Court occupying a site numbered 27 Madison Ave., but having its entrance on 25th Street. This set consists of 2 views; No. 2 of which is slightly further eastward to show a complete view of a 16-story loft building, No. 53-59 East 25th Street, that adjoins the N.W. corner of Fourth Ave.

November 26, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

title: Manhattan: 25th Street (East) - Madison

text:
25 to 17 Madison Ave., at, adjoining and south of the S.E. corner of East 25th Street, showing the demolition of 3 buildings that stood here. They were the Madison Ave., the Farragut and the Pullman Buildings. The Metropolitan Life Insurance Co., whose Annex occupies the balance of this block will utilize this site for construction.

September 1, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

27 Madison Ave., at the N.E. corner of East 25th Street, showing the Appellate Division of the Supreme Court. The entrance, as shown is on the 25th Street side.

September 15, 1937.

George D. Chinn.
